# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gestalt-visualization
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] According to Treisman, the first stage of the feature integration theory is the preattentive stage.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] During this stage, different parts of the brain automatically gather information about basic features (colors, shape, movement, size) that are found in the visual field.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] The idea that features are automatically separated appears counterintuitive.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] However, we are not aware of this process because it occurs early in perceptual processing, before we become conscious of the object.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] Evidence shows that preattentive focuses are accurate due to illusory conjunctions.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] The second stage of feature integration theory is the focused attention stage, where a subject combines individual features of an object to perceive the whole object.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] Combining individual features of an object requires attention, and selecting that object occurs within a "master map" of locations.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] The master map of locations contains all the locations in which features have been detected, with each location in the master map having access to the multiple feature maps.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] These multiple feature maps, or sub-maps, contain a large storage base of features.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] Features such as color, shape, orientation, sound, and movement are stored in these sub-maps.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] When attention is focused at a particular location on the map, the features currently in that position are attended to and are stored in "object files".
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] If the object is familiar, associations are made between the object and prior knowledge, which results in identification of that object.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] This top-down process, using prior knowledge to inform a current situation or decision, is paramount in either identifying or recognizing objects.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] In support of this stage, researchers often refer to patients with Bálint's syndrome.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] Due to damage in the parietal lobe, these people are only able to focus attention on individual objects, without deriving meaning from the overall visual field.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] Given a stimulus that requires combining features, people with Balint's syndrome are unable to focus attention long enough to combine the features, providing support for this stage of the theory.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] The combining of all feature identifiers to perceive all parts as one whole.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] This is possible through prior knowledge and cognitive mapping.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] When an item is seen within a known location and has features that people have knowledge of, then prior knowledge will help bring features all together to make sense of what is perceived.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] The case of R.M's damage to his parietal lobe, also known as Balint's syndrome, shows the incorporation of focused attention and combination of features in the role of attention.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] Treisman distinguishes between two kinds of visual search tasks, "feature search" and "conjunction search".
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] Feature searches can be performed fast and pre-attentively for targets defined by only one feature, such as color, shape, perceived direction of lighting, movement, or orientation.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] Features should "pop out" during search and should be able to form illusory conjunctions.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] Conversely, conjunction searches occur with the combination of two or more features and are identified serially.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] Conjunction search is much slower than feature search and requires conscious attention and effort.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] In multiple experiments, some referenced in this article, Treisman concluded that color, orientation, and intensity are features for which feature searches may be performed.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] To test the notion that attention plays a vital role in visual perception, Treisman and Schmidt (1982) designed an experiment to show that features may exist independently of one another early in processing.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] Participants were shown a picture involving four objects hidden by two black numbers.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] The display was flashed for one-fifth of a second followed by a random-dot masking field that appeared on screen to eliminate "any residual perception that might remain after the stimuli were turned off".
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] Participants were to report the black numbers they saw at each location where the shapes had previously been.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] The results of this experiment verified Treisman and Schmidt's hypothesis.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] In 18% of trials, participants reported seeing shapes "made up of a combination of features from two different stimuli", even when the stimuli had great differences; this is often referred to as an illusory conjunction.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] Specifically, illusory conjunctions occur in various situations.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] For example, you may identify a passing person wearing a red shirt and yellow hat and very quickly transform him or her into one wearing a yellow shirt and red hat.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] As previously mentioned, Balint's syndrome patients have provided support for the feature integration theory.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] This finding is in accordance with feature integration theory's prediction of how one with a lack of focused attention would erroneously combine features.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] If people use their prior knowledge or experience to perceive an object, they are less likely to make mistakes, or illusory conjunctions.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] To explain this phenomenon, Treisman and Souther (1986) conducted an experiment in which they presented three shapes to participants where illusory conjunctions could exist.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] Surprisingly, when she told participants that they were being shown a carrot, lake, and tire (in place of the orange triangle, blue oval, and black circle, respectively), illusory conjunctions did not exist.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] Treisman maintained that prior-knowledge played an important role in proper perception.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] Normally, bottom-up processing is used for identifying novel objects; but, once we recall prior knowledge, top-down processing is used.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] This explains why people are good at identifying familiar objects rather than unfamiliar.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] Research has demonstrated that congruency between features constrains the binding process.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] When participants were asked to bind incongruent features together (e.g., a small digit with a large physical size, or a color word written in a conflicting font color), they made significantly more errors than when binding congruent features.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] This phenomenon, termed the **binding congruency effect**, suggests that the cognitive system tends to suppress incongruent combinations, affecting the feature-integration.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] When identifying letters while reading, not only are their shapes picked up but also other features like their colors and surrounding elements.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] Individual letters are processed serially when spatially conjoined with another letter.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] The locations of each feature of a letter are not known in advance, even while the letter is in front of the reader.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] Since the location of the letter's features and/or the location of the letter is unknown, feature interchanges can occur if one is not attentively focused.
[src:gestalt-visualization/feature-integration-theory] This is known as lateral masking, which in this case, refers to a difficulty in separating a letter from the background.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Gestalt psychology is often associated with the idea that the whole is different from the sum of its parts.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] In Gestalt theory, information is perceived as wholes rather than disparate parts which are then processed summatively.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] As used in Gestalt psychology, the German word *Gestalt* (/ɡəˈʃtælt, -ˈʃtɑːlt/ *gə-SHTA(H)LT*; German: [ɡəˈʃtalt] ⓘ; meaning "form") is interpreted as "pattern" or "configuration".
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] It differs from Gestalt therapy, which is only peripherally linked to Gestalt psychology.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Max Wertheimer, Kurt Koffka, and Wolfgang Köhler founded Gestalt psychology in the early 20th century.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The dominant view in psychology at the time was structuralism, exemplified by the work of Hermann von Helmholtz, Wilhelm Wundt, and Edward B.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] "associationism," the view that more complex ideas arise from the association of simpler ideas.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Together, these three theories give rise to the view that the mind constructs all perceptions and abstract thoughts strictly from lower-level sensations, which are related solely by being associated closely in space and time.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The Gestaltists took issue with the widespread atomistic view that the aim of psychology should be to break consciousness down into putative basic elements.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] In contrast, the Gestalt psychologists believed that breaking psychological phenomena down into smaller parts would not lead to understanding psychology.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Instead, they viewed psychological phenomena as organized, structured wholes.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] They argued that the psychological "whole" has priority and that the "parts" are defined by the structure of the whole, rather than the other way round.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Gestalt theories of perception are based on human nature being inclined to understand objects as an entire structure rather than the sum of its parts.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Wertheimer had been a student of Austrian philosopher, Christian von Ehrenfels, a member of the School of Brentano.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Von Ehrenfels introduced the concept of Gestalt to philosophy and psychology in 1890, before the advent of Gestalt psychology as such.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Von Ehrenfels observed that a perceptual experience, such as perceiving a melody or a shape, is more than the sum of its sensory components.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] He claimed that, in addition to the sensory elements of the perception, there is something additional that is an element in its own right, despite in some sense being derived from the organization of the component sensory elements.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] He called it *Gestalt-qualität* or "form-quality." It is this *Gestalt-qualität* that, according to von Ehrenfels, allows a tune to be transposed to a new key, using completely different notes, while still retaining its identity.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The idea of a *Gestalt-qualität* has roots in theories by David Hume, Johann Wolfgang von Goethe, Immanuel Kant, David Hartley, and Ernst Mach.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Both von Ehrenfels and Edmund Husserl seem to have been inspired by Mach's work *Beiträge zur Analyse der Empfindungen* (Contributions to the Analysis of Sensations, 1886), in formulating their very similar concepts of *gestalt* and *figural moment*, respectively.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] By 1914, the first published references to Gestalt theory could be found in a footnote of Gabriele von Wartensleben's application of Gestalt theory to personality.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] She was a student at Frankfurt Academy for Social Sciences, who interacted deeply with Wertheimer and Köhler.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Through a series of experiments, Wertheimer discovered that a person observing a pair of alternating bars of light can, under the right conditions, experience the illusion of movement between one location and the other.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] He noted that this was a perception of motion absent any moving object.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Wertheimer's publication of these results in 1912 marks the beginning of Gestalt psychology.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] In comparison to von Ehrenfels and others who had used the term "gestalt" earlier in various ways, Wertheimer's unique contribution was to insist that the "gestalt" is perceptually primary.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The gestalt defines the parts from which it is composed, rather than being a secondary quality that emerges from those parts.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Wertheimer took the more radical position that one hears the melody first and only then may perceptually divide it up into notes.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Similarly, in vision, one sees the form of the circle first, with its apprehension not mediated by a process of part-summation.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Only after this primary apprehension might one notice that it is made up of lines or dots or stars.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The two men who served as Wertheimer's subjects in the phi experiments were Köhler and Koffka.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Köhler was an expert in physical acoustics, having studied under physicist Max Planck, but had taken his degree in psychology under Carl Stumpf.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Koffka was also a student of Stumpf's, having studied movement phenomena and psychological aspects of rhythm.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] In 1917, Köhler published the results of four years of research on learning in chimpanzees.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] In 1921, Koffka published a Gestalt-oriented text on developmental psychology, *Growth of the Mind*.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] With the help of American psychologist Robert Ogden, Koffka introduced the Gestalt point of view to an American audience in 1922 by way of a paper in *Psychological Bulletin*.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] It contains criticisms of then-current explanations of a number of problems of perception, and the alternatives offered by the Gestalt school.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Koffka moved to the United States in 1924, eventually settling at Smith College in 1927.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] In 1935, Koffka published his *Principles of Gestalt Psychology*.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] This textbook laid out the *Gestalt* vision of the scientific enterprise as a whole.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Science, he said, is not the simple accumulation of facts.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] What makes research scientific is the incorporation of facts into a theoretical structure.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The goal of the *Gestaltists* was to integrate the facts of inanimate nature, life, and mind into a single scientific structure.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Without incorporating the meaning of experience and behavior, Koffka believed that science would doom itself to trivialities in its investigation of human beings.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Having survived the Nazis up to the mid-1930s, all the core members of the Gestalt movement were forced out of Germany to the United States by 1935.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Köhler published another book, *Dynamics in Psychology*, in 1940 but thereafter the *Gestalt* movement suffered a series of setbacks.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Koffka died in 1941 and Wertheimer in 1943.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Wertheimer's long-awaited book on mathematical problem solving, *Productive Thinking,* was published posthumously in 1945, but Köhler was left to guide the movement without his two long-time colleagues.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Gestalt psychology differs from Gestalt therapy, which is only peripherally linked to Gestalt psychology.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The founders of Gestalt therapy, Fritz and Laura Perls, had worked with Kurt Goldstein, a neurologist who had applied principles of Gestalt psychology to the functioning of the organism.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Laura Perls had been a Gestalt psychologist before she became a psychoanalyst and before she began developing Gestalt therapy together with Fritz Perls.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The extent to which Gestalt psychology influenced Gestalt therapy is disputed.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] On one hand, Laura Perls preferred not to use the term "Gestalt" to name the emerging new therapy, because she thought that the Gestalt psychologists would object to it; on the other hand, Fritz and Laura Perls clearly adopted some of Goldstein's work.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] His work has no substantive relation to scientific Gestalt psychology.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] One form of psychotherapy that, unlike Gestalt therapy, is actually consistently based on Gestalt psychology is Gestalt theoretical psychotherapy.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The Gestalt psychologists practiced a set of theoretical and methodological principles that attempted to redefine the approach to psychological research.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] This is in contrast to investigations developed at the beginning of the 20th century, based on traditional scientific methodology, which divided the object of study into a set of elements that could be analyzed separately with the objective of reducing the complexity of this object.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The principle of totality asserts that conscious experience must be considered globally by taking into account all the physical and mental aspects of the individual simultaneously, because the nature of the mind demands that each component be considered as part of a system of dynamic relationships.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Thus, holism as fundamental aspect of Gestalt psychology.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Moreover, the perception of the nature of a part depends upon the whole in which it is embedded.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The maxim that the whole is more than the sum of its parts is not a precise description of the Gestaltist view.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The principle of psychophysical isomorphism hypothesizes that there is a correlation between conscious experience and cerebral activity.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Based on the principles, phenomenon experimental analysis was derived, which asserts that any psychological research should take phenomena as a starting point and not be solely focused on sensory qualities.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] A related principle is that of the biotic experiment, which establishes the need to conduct real experiments that sharply contrasted with and opposed classic laboratory experiments.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] This signified experimenting in natural situations, developed in real conditions, in which it would be possible to reproduce, with higher fidelity, what would be habitual for a subject.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The Gestaltists were the first to document and demonstrate empirically many facts about perception—including facts about the perception of movement, the perception of contour, perceptual constancy, and perceptual illusions.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Wertheimer's discovery of the phi phenomenon is one example of such a contribution.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The key principles of gestalt systems are emergence, reification, multistability and invariance.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] These principles are not necessarily separable modules to model individually, but they could be different aspects of a single unified dynamic mechanism.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Reification is the constructive or generative aspect of perception, by which the experienced object of perception contains more explicit spatial information than the sensory stimulus on which it is based.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] For instance, a triangle is perceived in picture **A**, though no triangle is there.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] In pictures **B** and **D** the eye recognizes disparate shapes as "belonging" to a single shape, in **C** a complete three-dimensional shape is seen, where in actuality no such thing is drawn.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Reification can be explained by progress in the study of illusory contours, which are treated by the visual system as "real" contours.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Multistability (or multistable perception) is the tendency of ambiguous perceptual experiences to pop back and forth between two or more alternative interpretations.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] This is seen, for example, in the Necker cube and Rubin's Figure/Vase illusion.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Other examples include the three-legged blivet, artworks by M.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Escher, and the appearance of flashing marquee lights moving first one direction and then suddenly the other.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Invariance is the property of perception whereby simple geometrical objects are recognized independent of rotation, translation, and scale, as well as several other variations such as elastic deformations, different lighting, and different component features.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] For example, the objects in **A** in the figure are all immediately recognized as the same basic shape, which is immediately distinguishable from the forms in **B**.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] They are even recognized despite perspective and elastic deformations as in **C**, and when depicted using different graphic elements as in **D**.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Computational theories of vision, such as those by David Marr, have provided alternate explanations of how perceived objects are classified.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Perceptual grouping (sometimes called perceptual segregation) is a form of perceptual organization.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Perceptual grouping is the process that determines how organisms perceive some parts of their perceptual fields as being more related than others, using such information for object detection.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The Gestaltists were the first psychologists to systematically study perceptual grouping.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] According to Gestalt psychologists, the fundamental principle of perceptual grouping is the law of ***Prägnanz***, also known as the law of good Gestalt.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] *Prägnanz* is a German word that directly translates to 'pithiness' and implies salience, conciseness, and orderliness.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The law of *Prägnanz* says that people tend to experience things as regular, orderly, symmetrical, and simple.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] In other words, human perception is biased towards simplicity.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Gestalt psychologists attempted to discover refinements of the law of **Prägnanz**, which involved writing down laws that predict the interpretation of sensation.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Wertheimer defined a few principles that explain the ways humans perceive objects based on similarity, proximity, and continuity.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The law of proximity states that when an individual perceives an assortment of objects, they perceive objects that are close to each other as forming a group.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] For example, in the figure illustrating the law of proximity, there are 72 circles, but we perceive the collection of circles in groups.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Specifically, we perceive that there is a group of 36 circles on the left side of the image and three groups of 12 circles on the right side of the image.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] This law is often used in advertising logos to emphasize which aspects of events are associated.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The law of similarity states that elements within an assortment of objects are perceptually grouped together if they are similar to each other in shape, colour, size etc.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] For example, the figure illustrating the law of similarity portrays 36 circles all equal distance apart from one another forming a square.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] In this depiction, 18 of the circles are shaded dark, and 18 of the circles are shaded light.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] We perceive the dark circles as grouped together and the light circles as grouped together, forming six horizontal lines within the square of circles.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] This perception of lines is due to the law of similarity.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Gestalt psychologists believed that humans tend to perceive objects as complete rather than focusing on the gaps that the object might contain.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] For example, a circle has good Gestalt in terms of completeness.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] However, we will also perceive an incomplete circle as a complete circle.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] That tendency to complete shapes and figures is called closure.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The law of closure states that individuals perceive objects such as shapes, letters, pictures, etc., as being whole when they are not complete.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Specifically, when parts of a whole picture are missing, our perception fills in the visual gap.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Research shows that the reason the mind completes a regular figure that is not perceived through sensation is to increase the regularity of surrounding stimuli.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] For example, the figure that depicts the law of closure portrays what we perceive as a circle on the left side of the image and a rectangle on the right side of the image.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] However, gaps are present in the shapes.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] If the law of closure did not exist, the image would depict an assortment of different lines with different lengths, rotations, and curvatures—but with the law of closure, we perceptually combine the lines into whole shapes.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] This law can be used effectively in logo design to create interest.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] For example, the letters of the IBM logo, consisting of horizontal blue lines, are immediately perceived as a single object.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The law of symmetry states that the mind perceives objects as being symmetrical and forming around a center point.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] It is perceptually pleasing to divide objects into an even number of symmetrical parts.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Therefore, when two symmetrical elements are unconnected the mind perceptually connects them to form a coherent shape.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Similarities between symmetrical objects increase the likelihood that objects are grouped to form a combined symmetrical object.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] For example, the figure depicting the law of symmetry shows a configuration of square and curled brackets.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] When the image is perceived, we tend to observe three pairs of symmetrical brackets rather than six individual brackets.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The law of common fate states that objects are perceived as lines that move along the smoothest path.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Experiments using the visual sensory modality found that the movement of elements of an object produces paths that individuals perceive that the objects are on.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] We perceive elements of objects to have trends of motion, which indicate the path that the object is on.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The law of continuity implies the grouping together of objects that have the same trend of motion and are therefore on the same path.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] For example, if there is an array of dots and half the dots are moving upward while the other half are moving downward, we would perceive the upward moving dots and the downward moving dots as two distinct units.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The law of continuity (also known as the law of good continuation) states that elements of objects tend to be grouped together, and therefore integrated into perceptual wholes if they are aligned within an object.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] In cases where there is an intersection between objects, individuals tend to perceive the two objects as two single uninterrupted entities.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Stimuli remain distinct even with overlap.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] We are less likely to group elements with sharp abrupt directional changes as being one object.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] For example, the figure depicting the law of continuity shows a configuration of two crossed keys.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] When the image is perceived, we tend to perceive the key in the background as a single uninterrupted key instead of two separate halves of a key.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The law of past experience implies that under some circumstances visual stimuli are categorized according to past experience.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] If objects tend to be observed within close proximity, or small temporal intervals, the objects are more likely to be perceived together.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] For example, the English language contains 26 letters that are grouped to form words using a set of rules.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] If an individual reads an English word they have never seen, they use the law of past experience to interpret the letters "L" and "I" as two letters beside each other, rather than using the law of closure to combine the letters and interpret the object as an uppercase U.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] An example of the Gestalt movement in effect, as it is both a process and result, is a music sequence.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] People are able to recognise a sequence of perhaps six or seven notes, despite them being transposed into a different tuning or key.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] An early theory of gestalt grouping principles in music was composer-theorist James Tenney's *Meta+Hodos* (1961).
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Auditory scene analysis as developed by Albert Bregman further extends a gestalt approach to the analysis of sound perception.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Figure-ground organization is a form of perceptual organization, which interprets perceptual elements in terms of their shapes and relative locations in the layout of surfaces in the 3-D world.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Figure-ground organization structures the perceptual field into a figure (standing out at the front of the perceptual field) and a background (receding behind the figure).
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Pioneering work on figure-ground organization was carried out by the Danish psychologist Edgar Rubin.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The Gestalt psychologists demonstrated that people tend to perceive as figures those parts of our perceptual fields that are convex, symmetric, small, and enclosed.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Gestalt psychology contributed to the scientific study of problem solving.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] In fact, the early experimental work of the Gestaltists in Germany marks the beginning of the scientific study of problem solving.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Later this experimental work continued through the 1960s and early 1970s with research conducted on relatively simple laboratory tasks of problem solving.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Max Wertheimer distinguished two kinds of thinking: productive thinking and reproductive thinking.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] *Productive thinking* is solving a problem based on insight—a quick, creative, unplanned response to situations and environmental interaction.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] *Reproductive thinking* is solving a problem deliberately based on previous experience and knowledge.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Reproductive thinking proceeds algorithmically—a problem solver reproduces a series of steps from memory, knowing that they will lead to a solution—or by trial and error.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Gestalt psychology struggled to precisely define terms like **Prägnanz**, to make specific behavioural predictions, and to articulate testable models of underlying neural mechanisms.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] It was criticized as being merely descriptive.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] These shortcomings led, by the mid-20th century, to growing dissatisfaction with Gestaltism and a subsequent decline in its impact on psychology.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Despite this decline, Gestalt psychology has formed the basis of much further research into the perception of patterns and objects and of research into behaviour, thinking, problem solving and psychopathology.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] He has no fovea, or region of greatest acuity in vision, upon which he must centre a part of the image...
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The frog does not seem to see or, at any rate, is not concerned with the detail of stationary parts of the world around him.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] He will starve to death surrounded by food if it is not moving.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] His choice of food is determined only by size and movement.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] He will leap to capture any object the size of an insect or worm, providing it moves like one.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] He can be fooled easily not only by a piece of dangled meat but by any moving small object...
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] He does remember a moving thing provided it stays within his field of vision and he is not distracted.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The lowest-level concepts related to visual perception for a human being probably differ little from the concepts of a frog.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The phenomenon of distortion of perception of an image stabilised on the retina gives some idea of the concepts of the subsequent levels of the hierarchy.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] When a person looks at an immobile object, "fixes" it with his eyes, the eyeballs do not remain absolutely immobile; they make small involuntary movements.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] As a result, the image of the object on the retina is constantly in motion, slowly drifting and jumping back to the point of maximum sensitivity.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The image "marks time" in the vicinity of this point.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The halo effect can be explained through the application of Gestalt theories to social information processing.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The constructive theories of social cognition are applied to the expectations of individuals.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] They have been perceived in this manner and the person judging the individual is continuing to view them in this positive manner.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Gestalt's theories of perception reinforce individuals' tendency to perceive actions and characteristics as a whole rather than isolated parts; therefore, humans are inclined to build a coherent and consistent impression of objects and behaviors in order to achieve an acceptable shape and form.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The halo effect is what forms patterns for individuals, the halo effect being classified as a cognitive bias which occurs during impression formation.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The halo effect can also be altered by physical characteristics, social status and many other characteristics.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Some of the central criticisms of Gestaltism are based on the preference Gestaltists are deemed to have for theory over data, and a lack of quantitative research supporting Gestalt ideas.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] This is not necessarily a fair criticism, as highlighted by a recent collection of quantitative research on Gestalt perception.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Researchers continue to test hypotheses about the mechanisms underlying Gestalt principles such as the principle of similarity.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Other important criticisms concern the lack of definition and support for the many physiological assumptions made by gestaltists and lack of theoretical coherence in modern Gestalt psychology.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] In some scholarly communities, such as cognitive psychology and computational neuroscience, gestalt theories of perception are criticized for being *descriptive* rather than *explanatory* in nature.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] For this reason, they are viewed by some as redundant or uninformative.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] For example, a textbook on visual perception states that, "The physiological theory of the gestaltists has fallen by the wayside, leaving us with a set of descriptive principles, but without a model of perceptual processing.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Indeed, some of their 'laws' of perceptual organisation today sound vague and inadequate.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Murray, has argued that Gestalt psychologists first discovered many principles later championed by cognitive psychology, including schemas and prototypes.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Another psychologist has argued that the Gestalt psychologists made a lasting contribution by showing how the study of illusions can help scientists understand essential aspects of how the visual system *normally* functions, not merely how it breaks down.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The gestalt laws are used in several visual design fields, such as user interface design and cartography.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] The laws of similarity and proximity can, for example, be used as guides for placing radio buttons.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] They may also be used in designing computers and software for more intuitive human use.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] Examples include the design and layout of a desktop's shortcuts in rows and columns.
[src:gestalt-visualization/gestalt-psychology] In map design, principles of **Prägnanz** or grouping are crucial for implying a conceptual order to the portrayed geographic features, thus facilitating the intended use of the map.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] In addition, **Narrative visualization** is a method that uses visual elements such as charts, graphs, maps and the like to convey data or information.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] This approach blends data analysis, storytelling, and visualization to present information through structured narrative flows- *using visuals not just to present statistics, but to tell a story through data*.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Its goal is to help people identify trends, patterns, and relationships in data through a compelling story-driven visual experience.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Emerging technologies like virtual, augmented and mixed reality have the potential to make information visualization more immersive, intuitive, interactive and easily manipulable and thus enhance the user's visual perception and cognition.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Effective data visualization is well-sourced, appropriately contextualized, and presented in a simple, uncluttered manner.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] The underlying data is accurate and up-to-date to ensure insights are reliable.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Graphical items are well-chosen and aesthetically appealing, with shapes, colors and other visual elements used deliberately in a meaningful and non-distracting manner.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] The visuals are accompanied by supporting texts.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Verbal and graphical components complement each other to ensure clear, quick and memorable understanding.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Effective information visualization is aware of the needs and expertise level of the target audience.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Data scientists, analysts and data mining specialists use data visualization to check data quality, find errors, unusual gaps, missing values, clean data, explore the structures and features of data, and assess outputs of data-driven models.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization can be part of *data storytelling*, where they are paired with a narrative structure, to contextualize the analyzed data and communicate insights gained from analyzing it to convince the audience into making a decision or taking action.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization is interdisciplinary, it incorporates principles found in descriptive statistics, visual communication, graphic design, cognitive science and, interactive computer graphics and human-computer interaction.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Since effective visualization requires design skills, statistical skills and computing skills, it is both an art and a science.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Visual analytics combines statistical data analysis, data and information visualization, and human analytical reasoning through interactive visual interfaces to help users reach conclusions, gain actionable insights and make informed decisions which are otherwise difficult for computers to do.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Research into how people read and misread types of visualizations helps to determine what types and features of visualizations are most understandable and effective.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Unintentionally poor or intentionally misleading and deceptive visualizations can function as powerful tools which disseminate misinformation, manipulate public perception and divert public opinion.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Thus data visualization literacy has become an important component of data and information literacy in the information age akin to the roles played by textual, mathematical and visual literacy in the past.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] The field of data and information visualization has emerged "from research in human–computer interaction, computer science, graphics, visual design, psychology, photography and business methods.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] It is increasingly applied as a critical component in scientific research, digital libraries, data mining, financial data analysis, market studies, manufacturing production control, and drug discovery".
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization presumes that "visual representations and interaction techniques take advantage of the human eye's broad bandwidth pathway into the mind to allow users to see, explore, and understand large amounts of information at once.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Data analysis is an indispensable part of all applied research and problem solving in industry.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Among these approaches, information visualization, or visual data analysis, is the most reliant on the cognitive skills of human analysts, and allows the discovery of unstructured actionable insights that are limited only by human imagination and creativity.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] The analyst does not have to learn any sophisticated methods to be able to interpret the visualizations of the data.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Information visualization is also a hypothesis generation scheme, which can be, and is typically followed by more analytical or formal analysis, such as statistical hypothesis testing.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] To communicate information clearly and efficiently, data visualization uses statistical graphics, plots, information graphics and other tools.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Numerical data may be encoded using dots, lines, or bars, to visually communicate a quantitative message.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Effective visualization helps users analyze and reason about data and evidence.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] It makes complex data more accessible, understandable, and usable, but can also be reductive.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Users may have particular analytical tasks, such as making comparisons or understanding causality, and the design principle of the graphic (i.e., showing comparisons or showing causality) follows the task.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Tables are generally used where users will look up a specific measurement, while charts of various types are used to show patterns or relationships in the data for one or more variables.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Data visualization refers to the techniques used to communicate data or information by encoding it as visual objects (e.g., points, lines, or bars) contained in graphics.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] The goal is to communicate information clearly and efficiently to users.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] It is one of the steps in data analysis or data science.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] According to Vitaly Friedman (2008) the "main goal of data visualization is to communicate information clearly and effectively through graphical means.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] It doesn't mean that data visualization needs to look boring to be functional or extremely sophisticated to look beautiful.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] To convey ideas effectively, both aesthetic form and functionality need to go hand in hand, providing insights into a rather sparse and complex data set by communicating its key aspects in a more intuitive way.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Yet designers often fail to achieve a balance between form and function, creating gorgeous data visualizations which fail to serve their main purpose — to communicate information".
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Wattenberg suggested that an ideal visualization should not only communicate clearly, but stimulate viewer engagement and attention.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Data visualization is closely related to information graphics, information visualization, scientific visualization, exploratory data analysis and statistical graphics.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] In the new millennium, data visualization has become an active area of research, teaching and development.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] (2002), it has united scientific and information visualization.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] In the commercial environment data visualization is often referred to as dashboards.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Infographics are another very common form of data visualization.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Edward Tufte has explained that users of information displays are executing particular *analytical tasks* such as making comparisons.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] The *design principle* of the information graphic should support the analytical task.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] As William Cleveland and Robert McGill show, different graphical elements accomplish this more or less effectively.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] For example, dot plots and bar charts outperform pie charts.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] In his 1983 book *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information*, Edward Tufte defines 'graphical displays' and principles for effective graphical display in the following passage: "Excellence in statistical graphics consists of complex ideas communicated with clarity, precision, and efficiency.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] For example, the Minard diagram shows the losses suffered by Napoleon's army in the 1812–1813 period.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Six variables are plotted: the size of the army, its location on a two-dimensional surface (x and y), time, the direction of movement, and temperature.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] The line width illustrates a comparison (size of the army at points in time), while the temperature axis suggests a cause of the change in army size.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] This multivariate display on a two-dimensional surface tells a story that can be grasped immediately while identifying the source data to build credibility.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Not applying these principles may result in misleading graphs, distorting the message, or supporting an erroneous conclusion.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] According to Tufte, chartjunk refers to the extraneous interior decoration of the graphic that does not enhance the message or gratuitous three-dimensional or perspective effects.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Needlessly separating the explanatory key from the image itself, requiring the eye to travel back and forth from the image to the key, is a form of "administrative debris." The ratio of "data to ink" should be maximized, erasing non-data ink where feasible.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] The Congressional Budget Office summarized several best practices for graphical displays in a June 2014 presentation.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] These included: a) Knowing your audience; b) Designing graphics that can stand alone outside the report's context; and c) Designing graphics that communicate the key messages in the report.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] For greatest efficiency and simplicity of design and user experience, this readability is enhanced through the use of bijective mapping in that design of the image elements - where the mapping of representational element to data variable is unique.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Kosara (2007) also identifies the need for a visualisation to be "recognisable as a visualisation and not appear to be something else".
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] He also states that recognisability and readability may not always be required in all types of visualisation e.g.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] "informative art" (which would still meet all three above criteria but might not look like a visualisation) or "artistic visualisation" (which similarly is still based on non-visual data to create an image, but may not be readable or recognisable).
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Ranking: Categorical subdivisions are ranked in ascending or descending order, such as a ranking of sales performance (the *measure*) by sales persons (the *category*, with each sales person a *categorical subdivision*) during a single period.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used to show the comparison across the sales persons.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Part-to-whole: Categorical subdivisions are measured as a ratio to the whole (i.e., a percentage out of 100%).
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] A pie chart or bar chart can show the comparison of ratios, such as the market share represented by competitors in a market.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Deviation: Categorical subdivisions are compared against a reference, such as a comparison of actual vs. budget expenses for several departments of a business for a given time period.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] A bar chart can show comparison of the actual versus the reference amount.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Frequency distribution: Shows the number of observations of a particular variable for given interval, such as the number of years in which the stock market return is between intervals such as 0–10%, 11–20%, etc.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] A histogram, a type of bar chart, may be used for this analysis.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] A boxplot helps visualize key statistics about the distribution, such as median, quartiles, outliers, etc.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Correlation: Comparison between observations represented by two variables (X,Y) to determine if they tend to move in the same or opposite directions.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] For example, plotting unemployment (X) and inflation (Y) for a sample of months.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] A scatter plot is typically used for this message.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Nominal comparison: Comparing categorical subdivisions in no particular order, such as the sales volume by product code.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used for this comparison.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Geographic or geospatial: Comparison of a variable across a map or layout, such as the unemployment rate by state or the number of persons on the various floors of a building.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Analysts reviewing a set of data may consider whether some or all of the messages and graphic types above are applicable to their task and audience.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] The process of trial and error to identify meaningful relationships and messages in the data is part of exploratory data analysis.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] A human can distinguish differences in line length, shape, orientation, distances, and color (hue) readily without significant processing effort; these are referred to as "pre-attentive attributes".
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] For example, it may require significant time and effort ("attentive processing") to identify the number of times the digit "5" appears in a series of numbers; but if that digit is different in size, orientation, or color, instances of the digit can be noted quickly through pre-attentive processing.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Compelling graphics take advantage of pre-attentive processing and attributes and the relative strength of these attributes.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] For example, since humans can more easily process differences in line length than surface area, it may be more effective to use a bar chart (which takes advantage of line length to show comparison) rather than pie charts (which use surface area to show comparison).
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Almost all data visualizations are created for human consumption.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Knowledge of human perception and cognition is necessary when designing intuitive visualizations.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Cognition refers to processes in human beings like perception, attention, learning, memory, thought, concept formation, reading, and problem solving.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Human visual processing is efficient in detecting changes and making comparisons between quantities, sizes, shapes and variations in lightness.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] When properties of symbolic data are mapped to visual properties, humans can browse through large amounts of data efficiently.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] It is estimated that 2/3 of the brain's neurons can be involved in visual processing.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Proper visualization provides a different approach to show potential connections, relationships, etc. which are not as obvious in non-visualized quantitative data.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Visualization can become a means of data exploration.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Studies have shown individuals used on average 19% less cognitive resources, and 4.5% better able to recall details when comparing data visualization with text.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] There is no comprehensive history of data visualization.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] There are no accounts that span the entire development of visual thinking and visual representation of data, and which collate the contributions of disparate disciplines.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Michael Friendly and Daniel Denis of York University are engaged in a project that attempts to provide a comprehensive history of visualization.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Data visualization is not a modern development.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Since prehistory, stellar data, or information such as location of stars were visualized on the walls of caves (such as those found in Lascaux Cave in Southern France) since the Pleistocene era.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Physical artefacts such as Mesopotamian clay tokens (5500 BC), Inca quipus (2600 BC) and Marshall Islands stick charts (n.d.) can also be considered as visualizing quantitative information.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] The first documented data visualization can be tracked back to 1160 B.C. with the Turin Papyrus Map which accurately illustrates the distribution of geological resources and provides information about quarrying of those resources.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Such maps can be categorized as thematic cartography, which is a type of data visualization that presents and communicates specific data and information through a geographical illustration designed to show a particular theme connected with a specific geographic area.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Earliest documented forms of data visualization were various thematic maps from different cultures and ideograms and hieroglyphs that provided and allowed interpretation of information illustrated.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] For example, Linear B tablets of Mycenae provided a visualization of information regarding Late Bronze Age era trades in the Mediterranean.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] The idea of coordinates was used by ancient Egyptian surveyors in laying out towns, earthly and heavenly positions were located by something akin to latitude and longitude at least by 200 BC, and the map projection of a spherical Earth into latitude and longitude by Claudius Ptolemy [c.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] 165] in Alexandria would serve as reference standards until the 14th century.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] The invention of paper and parchment allowed further development of visualizations.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] One graph from the 10th or possibly 11th century is an illustration of planetary movements, used in an appendix of a textbook in monastery schools.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] The graph apparently was meant to represent a plot of the inclinations of the planetary orbits as a function of the time.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] For this purpose, the zone of the zodiac was represented on a plane with a horizontal line divided into thirty parts as the time or longitudinal axis.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] The vertical axis designates the width of the zodiac.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] The horizontal scale appears to have been chosen for each planet individually for the periods cannot be reconciled.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] The accompanying text refers only to the amplitudes.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] The curves are apparently not related in time.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] By the 16th century, techniques and instruments for precise observation and measurement of physical quantities, and geographic and celestial position were well-developed (for example, a "wall quadrant" constructed by Tycho Brahe [1546–1601], covering an entire wall in his observatory).
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Particularly important were the development of triangulation and other methods to determine mapping locations accurately.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Very early, the measure of time led scholars to develop innovative way of visualizing the data (e.g.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Lorenz Codomann in 1596, Johannes Temporarius in 1596).
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Mathematicians René Descartes and Pierre de Fermat developed analytic geometry and two-dimensional coordinate system which heavily influenced the practical methods of displaying and calculating values.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Fermat and Blaise Pascal's work on statistics and probability theory laid the groundwork for what we now conceptualize as data.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] These developments helped William Playfair, who saw potential for graphical communication of quantitative data, to generate and develop graphical methods of statistics.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] In 1786, Playfair published the first presentation graphics.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] In the second half of the 20th century, Jacques Bertin used quantitative graphs to represent information "intuitively, clearly, accurately, and efficiently".
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] John Tukey and Edward Tufte pushed the bounds of data visualization; Tukey with his new statistical approach of exploratory data analysis and Tufte with his book "The Visual Display of Quantitative Information" paved the way for refining data visualization techniques for more than statisticians.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] With the progression of technology came the progression of data visualization; starting with hand-drawn visualizations and evolving into more technical applications – including interactive designs leading to software visualization.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] The modern study of visualization started with computer graphics, which "has from its beginning been used to study scientific problems.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] However, in its early days the lack of graphics power often limited its usefulness.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] The recent emphasis on visualization started in 1987 with the special issue of Computer Graphics on Visualization in *Scientific Computing*.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Since then there have been several conferences and workshops, co-sponsored by the IEEE Computer Society and ACM SIGGRAPH".
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] They have been devoted to the general topics of data visualization, information visualization and scientific visualization, and more specific areas such as volume visualization.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Programs like SAS, SOFA, R, Minitab, Cornerstone and more allow for data visualization in the field of statistics.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Other data visualization applications, more focused and unique to individuals, programming languages such as D3, Python (through matplotlib, seaborn) and JavaScript and Java(through JavaFX) help to make the visualization of quantitative data a possibility.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Private schools have also developed programs to meet the demand for learning data visualization and associated programming libraries, including free programs like The Data Incubator or paid programs like General Assembly.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Beginning with the symposium "Data to Discovery" in 2013, ArtCenter College of Design, Caltech and JPL in Pasadena have run an annual program on interactive data visualization.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] The program asks: How can interactive data visualization help scientists and engineers explore their data more effectively?
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] How can computing, design, and design thinking help maximize research results?
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] What methodologies are most effective for leveraging knowledge from these fields?
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] In recent years, with the increasing popularity of games, data and information visualization has been gradually applied in the gaming industry through the use of analytical tools to assess player statistics and game performance, which are visualized in the form of health points, maps, and diagrams.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] The data is then collected and stored by developers.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] The implementation of these tools in gaming assists developers in improving user experience and in the development and updating of newer games.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Data visualization involves specific terminology, some of which is derived from statistics.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] The distinction between quantitative and categorical variables is important because the two types require different methods of visualization.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Two primary types of information displays are tables and graphs.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Eppler and Lengler have developed the "Periodic Table of Visualization Methods," an interactive chart displaying various data visualization methods.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] It includes six types of data visualization methods: data, information, concept, strategy, metaphor and compound.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Interactive data visualization has been a pursuit of statisticians since the late 1960s.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Examples of the developments can be found on the American Statistical Association video lending library.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] There are different approaches on the scope of data visualization.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] One common focus is on information presentation, such as Friedman (2008).
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Friendly (2008) presumes two main parts of data visualization: statistical graphics, and thematic cartography.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] All these subjects are closely related to graphic design and information representation.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Within The Harvard Business Review, Scott Berinato developed a framework to approach data visualisation.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] To start thinking visually, users must consider two questions; 1) What you have and 2) what you're doing.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] The first step is identifying what data you want visualised.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] It is data-driven like profit over the past ten years or a conceptual idea like how a specific organisation is structured.
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Once this question is answered one can then focus on whether they are trying to communicate information (declarative visualisation) or trying to figure something out (exploratory visualisation).
[src:gestalt-visualization/information-visualization-p01] Scott Berinato combines these questions to give four types of visual communication that each have their own goals.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] The reasons are unclear as to why certain information proceeds from pre-attentive to attentive processing while other information does not.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] It is generally accepted that the selection involves an interaction between the salience of a stimulus and person's current intentions and/or goals.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] Two models of pre-attentive processing are pure-capture and contingent-capture.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] The "pure-capture" model focuses on stimulus salience.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] If certain properties of a stimulus stand out from its background, the stimulus has a higher chance of being selected for attentive processing.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] This is sometimes referred to as "bottom-up" processing, as it is the properties of the stimuli which affect selection.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] Since things that affect pre-attentive processing do not necessarily correlate with things that affect attention, stimulus salience may be more important than conscious goals.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] For example, pre-attentive processing is slowed by sleep deprivation while attention, although less focused, is not slowed.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] Furthermore, when searching for a particular visual stimulus among a variety of visual distractions, people often have more trouble finding what they are looking for if one or more of the distractions is particularly salient.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] For example, it is easier to locate a bright, green circle (which is salient) among distractor circles if they are all grey (a bland color) than it is to locate a green circle among distractor circles if some are red (also salient colour).
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] This is thought to occur because the salient red circles attract our attention away from the target green circle.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] However, this is difficult to prove because when given a target (like the green circle) to search for in a laboratory experiment, participants may generalize the task to searching for anything that stands out, rather than solely searching for the target.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] If this happens, the conscious goal becomes finding anything that stands out, which would direct the person's attention towards red distractor circles as well as the green target.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] This means that a person's goal, rather than the salience of the stimuli, could be causing the delayed ability to find the target.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] The "contingent-capture" model emphasizes the idea that a person's current intentions and/or goals affect the speed and efficiency of pre-attentive processing.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] The brain directs an individual's attention towards stimuli with features that fit in with their goals.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] Consequently, these stimuli will be processed faster at the pre-attentive stage and will be more likely to be selected for attentive processing.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] Since this model focuses on the importance of conscious processes (rather than properties of the stimulus itself) in selecting information for attentive processing, it is sometimes called "top-down" selection.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] In support of this model, it has been shown that a target stimulus can be located faster if it is preceded by the presentation of a similar, priming stimulus.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] For example, if an individual is shown the color green and then required to find a green circle among distractors, the initial exposure to the color will make it easier to find the green circle.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] This is because they are already thinking about and envisioning the color green, so when it shows up again as the green circle, their brain readily directs its attention towards it.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] This suggests that processing an initial stimulus speeds up a person's ability to select a similar target from pre-attentive processing.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] However, it could be that the speed of pre-attentive processing itself is not affected by the first stimulus, but rather that people are simply able to quickly abandon dissimilar stimuli, enabling them to re-engage to the correct target more quickly.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] This would mean that the difference in reaction time occurs at the attentive level, after pre-attentive processing and stimulus selection has already taken place.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] Information for pre-attentive processing is detected through the senses.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] In the visual system, the receptive fields at the back of the eye (retina) transfer the image via axons to the thalamus, specifically the lateral geniculate nuclei.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] The image then travels to the primary visual cortex and continues on to be processed by the visual association cortex.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] At each stage, the image is processed with increasing complexity.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] Pre-attentive processing starts with the retinal image; this image is magnified as it moves from retina to the cortex of the brain.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] Shades of light and dark are processed in the lateral geniculate nuclei of the thalamus.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] Simple and complex cells in the brain process boundary and surface information by deciphering the image's contrast, orientation, and edges.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] When the image hits the fovea, it is highly magnified, facilitating object recognition.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] The images in the periphery are less clear but help to create a complete image used for scene perception.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] Visual scene segmentation is a pre-attentive process where stimuli are grouped together into specific objects against a background.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] Figure and background regions of an image activate different processing centres: figures use the lateral occipital areas (which involve object processing) and background engages dorso-medial areas.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] Visual pre-attentive processing uses a distinct memory mechanism.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] When a stimulus is presented consecutively, the stimulus is perceived at a faster rate than if different stimuli are presented consecutively.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] The theory behind this is called the dimension-weighting account (DWA) where each time a specific stimulus (i.e. color) is presented it contributes to the weight of the stimuli.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] More presentations increase the weight of the stimuli, and therefore, subsequently decrease the reaction time to the stimulus.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] The dimensional-weighting system, which calculates pre-attentive processing for our visual system, codes the stimulus and thus directs attention to the stimulus with the most weight.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] Visual pre-attentive processing is also involved in the perception of emotion.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] Human beings are social creatures and are very adept at critiquing facial expressions.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] We have the ability to unconsciously process emotional stimuli and equate the stimuli, such as a face, with meaning.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] The auditory system is also very important in accumulating information for pre-attentive processing.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] When a person's eardrum is struck by incoming sound waves, it vibrates.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] This sends messages, via the auditory nerve, to the brain for pre-attentive processing.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] The ability to adequately filter information from pre-attentive processing to attentive processing is necessary for the normal development of social skills.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] For acoustic pre-attentive processing, the temporal cortex was believed to be the main site of activation; however, recent evidence has indicated involvement of the frontal cortex as well.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] The frontal cortex is predominantly associated with attentional processing, but it may also be involved in pre-attentive processing of complex or salient acoustic stimuli.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] For example, detecting slight variations in complex musical patterns has been shown to activate the right ventromedial prefrontal cortex.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] It has been shown that in acoustic pre-attentive processing there is some degree of lateralization.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] The left hemisphere responds more to temporal acoustic information whereas the right hemisphere responds to the frequency of auditory information.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] Also, there is lateralization in the perception of speech which is left hemisphere dominant for pre-attentive processing.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] Vision, sound, smell, touch, and taste are processed together pre-attentively when more than one sensory stimuli are present.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] This multisensory integration increases activity in the superior temporal sulcus (STS), thalamus, and superior colliculus.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] Specifically, the pre-attentive process of multisensory integration works jointly with attention to activate brain regions such as the STS.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] Multisensory integration seems to give a person the advantage of greater comprehension if both auditory and visual stimuli are being processed together.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] But it is important to note that multisensory integration is affected by what a person pays attention to and their current goals.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] Training can lead to changes in activity and brain structures involved in pre-attentive processing.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] Professional musicians, in particular, show larger ERP (Event-related potential) responses to deviations in auditory stimuli and have possibly related structural differences in their brains (Heschl's gyrus, corpus callosum, and pyramidal tracts).
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] This plasticity of pre-attentive processing has also been shown in perception.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] Using EEG (electroencephalography) methods in pre-attentive colour perception, a study observed how easy it was for bilinguals to adapt to the linguistic constructs of a different culture.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] This means that pre-attentive processes are not hard-wired but malleable.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] Deficits in the transition from pre-attentive processing to attentive processing are associated with disorders such as schizophrenia, Alzheimer's disease, and autism.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] Abnormal prefrontal cortex function in individuals with schizophrenia results in the inability to use pre-attentive processing to recognize familiar auditory stimuli as non-threatening.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] Individuals with schizophrenia with positive symptoms have a greater capability of pre-attentively processing emotionally negative odors.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] This heightened ability to distinguish odors seems to be involved in their hypersensitivity to threatening situations.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] Alzheimer's disease is typically thought to affect high-level brain functioning (like memory) but can also have negative impacts on visual pre-attentive processing.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] Some of the difficulties with social interaction seen in autistic individuals may be due to an impairment in filtration of pre-attentive auditory information.
[src:gestalt-visualization/pre-attentive-processing] For example, they often have difficulty following a conversation as they cannot distinguish which parts are important and are easily distracted by other sounds.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] The **principles of grouping** (or **Gestalt laws of grouping**) are a set of principles in psychology, first proposed by Gestalt psychologists to account for the observation that humans naturally perceive objects as organized patterns and objects, a principle known as Prägnanz.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] The German term *Gestalt* in psychological contexts means *shape*, *pattern*, *configuration*.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] Gestalt psychologists argued that these principles exist because the mind has an innate disposition to perceive patterns in the stimulus based on certain rules.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] These principles are organized into five categories: Proximity, Similarity, Continuity, Closure, and Connectedness.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] The Gestalt law of proximity states that "objects or shapes that are close to one another appear to form groups".
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] Even if the shapes, sizes, and objects are radically different, they will appear as a group if they are close.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] The principle of similarity states that perception lends itself to seeing stimuli that physically resemble each other as part of the same object.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] This allows for people to distinguish between adjacent and overlapping objects based on their visual texture and resemblance.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] Other stimuli that have different features are generally not perceived as part of the object.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] An example of this is a large area of land used by numerous independent farmers to grow crops.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] The human brain uses similarity to distinguish between objects which might lie adjacent to or overlap with each other based upon their visual texture.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] Each farmer may use a unique planting style which distinguishes his field from another.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] Another example is a field of flowers which differ only by color.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] The principles of similarity and proximity often work together to form a Visual Hierarchy.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] Either principle can dominate the other, depending on the application and combination of the two.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] For example, in the grid to the left, the similarity principle dominates the proximity principle; the rows are probably seen before the columns.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] The principle of closure refers to the mind's tendency to see complete figures or forms even if a picture is incomplete, partially hidden by other objects, or if part of the information needed to make a complete picture in the minds is missing.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] For example, if part of a shape's border is missing people still tend to see the shape as completely enclosed by the border and ignore the gaps.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] This reaction stems from the mind's natural tendency to recognize patterns that are familiar and thus fill in any information that may be missing.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] Closure is also thought to have evolved from ancestral survival instincts in that if one was to partially see a predator their mind would automatically complete the picture and know that it was a time to react to potential danger even if not all the necessary information was readily available.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] When there is an intersection between two or more objects, people tend to perceive each object as a single uninterrupted object.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] This allows differentiation of stimuli even when they come in visual overlap.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] Humans have a tendency to group and organize lines or curves that follow an established direction over those defined by sharp and abrupt changes in direction.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] When visual elements are seen moving in the same direction at the same rate (optical flow), perception associates the movement as part of the same stimulus.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] For example, birds may be distinguished from their background as a single flock because they are moving in the same direction and at the same velocity, even when each bird is seen—from a distance—as little more than a dot.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] The moving 'dots' appear to be part of a unified whole.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] Similarly, two flocks of birds can cross each other in a viewer's visual field, but they will nonetheless continue to be experienced as separate flocks because each bird has a direction common to its flock.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] This allows people to make out moving objects even when other details (such as the objects color or outline) are obscured.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] This ability likely arose from the evolutionary need to distinguish a camouflaged predator from its background.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] The principle of good form refers to the tendency to group together forms of similar shape, pattern, color, etc.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] Even in cases where two or more forms clearly overlap, the human brain interprets them in a way that allows people to differentiate different patterns and/or shapes.
[src:gestalt-visualization/principles-of-grouping] An example would be a pile of presents where a dozen packages of different size and shape are wrapped in just three or so patterns of wrapping paper, or the Olympic Rings.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Much previous literature on visual search used reaction time in order to measure the time it takes to detect the target amongst its distractors.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] An example of this could be a green square (the target) amongst a set of red circles (the distractors).
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Many visual search paradigms have therefore used eye movement as a means to measure the degree of attention given to stimuli.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] However, eyes can move independently of attention, and therefore eye movement measures do not completely capture the role of attention.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Feature search (also known as "disjunctive" or "efficient" search) is a visual search process that focuses on identifying a previously requested target amongst distractors that differ from the target by a unique visual feature such as color, shape, orientation, or size.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] An example of a feature search task is asking a participant to identify a white square (target) surrounded by black squares (distractors).
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] In this type of visual search, the distractors are characterized by the same visual features.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] The efficiency of feature search in regards to reaction time (RT) and accuracy depends on the "pop out" effect, bottom-up processing, and parallel processing.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] However, the efficiency of feature search is unaffected by the number of distractors present.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] The "pop out" effect is an element of feature search that characterizes the target's ability to stand out from surrounding distractors due to its unique feature.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Bottom-up processing, which is the processing of information that depends on input from the environment, explains how one utilizes feature detectors to process characteristics of the stimuli and differentiate a target from its distractors.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] This draw of visual attention towards the target due to bottom-up processes is known as "saliency." Lastly, parallel processing is the mechanism that then allows one's feature detectors to work simultaneously in identifying the target.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Conjunction search (also known as inefficient or serial search) is a visual search process that focuses on identifying a previously requested target surrounded by distractors possessing no distinct features from the target itself.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] An example of a conjunction search task is having a person identify a green X (target) amongst distractors composed of purple Xs (same shape) and green Os (same color).
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Unlike feature search, conjunction search involves distractors (or groups of distractors) that may differ from each other but exhibit at least one common feature with the target.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] The efficiency of conjunction search in regards to reaction time (RT) and accuracy is dependent on the distractor-ratio and the number of distractors present.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] As the distractors represent the differing individual features of the target more equally amongst themselves (distractor-ratio effect), reaction time(RT) increases and accuracy decreases.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] As the number of distractors present increases, the reaction time (RT) increases and the accuracy decreases.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] However, with practice the original reaction time (RT) restraints of conjunction search tend to show improvement.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] In the early stages of processing, conjunction search utilizes bottom-up processes to identify pre-specified features amongst the stimuli.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] These processes are then overtaken by a more serial process of consciously evaluating the indicated features of the stimuli in order to properly allocate one's focal spatial attention towards the stimulus that most accurately represents the target.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] In many cases, top-down processing affects conjunction search by eliminating stimuli that are incongruent with one's previous knowledge of the target-description, which in the end allows for more efficient identification of the target.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] In everyday situations, people are most commonly searching their visual fields for targets that are familiar to them.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] When it comes to searching for familiar stimuli, top-down processing allows one to more efficiently identify targets with greater complexity than can be represented in a feature or conjunction search task.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Top-down processes allowed study participants to access prior knowledge regarding shape recognition of the letter N and quickly eliminate the stimuli that matched their knowledge.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] In the real world, one must use prior knowledge everyday in order to accurately and efficiently locate objects such as phones, keys, etc. among a much more complex array of distractors.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] While bottom-up processes may come into play when identifying objects that are not as familiar to a person, overall top-down processing highly influences visual searches that occur in everyday life.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Familiarity can play especially critical roles when parts of objects are not visible (as when objects are partly hidden from view because they are behind other objects).
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Visual information from hidden parts can be recalled from long-term memory and used to facilitate search for familiar objects.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] It is also possible to measure the role of attention within visual search experiments by calculating the slope of reaction time over the number of distractors present.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Generally, when high levels of attention are required when looking at a complex array of stimuli (conjunction search), the slope increases as reaction times increase.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] For simple visual search tasks (feature search), the slope decreases due to reaction times being fast and requiring less attention.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] However, the use of a reaction time slope to measure attention is controversial because non-attentional factors can also affect reaction time slope.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] One obvious way to select visual information is to turn towards it, also known as visual orienting.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] This may be a movement of the head and/or eyes towards the visual stimulus, called a saccade.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Through a process called foveation, the eyes fixate on the object of interest, making the image of the visual stimulus fall on the fovea of the eye, the central part of the retina with the sharpest visual acuity.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Visual search relies primarily on endogenous orienting because participants have the goal to detect the presence or absence of a specific target object in an array of other distracting objects.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] These findings indicate that attention plays a critical role in understanding visual search.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Subsequently, competing theories of attention have come to dominate visual search discourse.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] The environment contains a vast amount of information.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] We are limited in the amount of information we are able to process at any one time, so it is therefore necessary that we have mechanisms by which extraneous stimuli can be filtered and only relevant information attended to.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] In the study of attention, psychologists distinguish between pre-attentive and attentional processes.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Pre-attentive processes are evenly distributed across all input signals, forming a kind of "low-level" attention.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Attentional processes are more selective and can only be applied to specific preattentive input.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] A large part of the current debate in visual search theory centres on selective attention and what the visual system is capable of achieving without focal attention.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] A popular explanation for the different reaction times of feature and conjunction searches is the feature integration theory (FIT), introduced by Treisman and Gelade in 1980.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] This theory proposes that certain visual features are registered early, automatically, and are coded rapidly in parallel across the visual field using pre-attentive processes.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Experiments show that these features include luminance, colour, orientation, motion direction, and velocity, as well as some simple aspects of form.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] For example, when locating an orange square among blue squares and orange triangles, neither the colour feature "orange" nor the shape feature "square" is sufficient to locate the search target.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Instead, one must integrate information of both colour and shape to locate the target.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Evidence that attention and thus later visual processing is needed to integrate two or more features of the same object is shown by the occurrence of illusory conjunctions, or when features do not combine correctly.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] For example, if a display of a green X and a red O are flashed on a screen so briefly that the later visual process of a serial search with focal attention cannot occur, the observer may report seeing a red X and a green O.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] The FIT is a dichotomy because of the distinction between its two stages: the preattentive and attentive stages.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Preattentive processes are those performed in the first stage of the FIT model, in which the simplest features of the object are being analyzed, such as color, size, and arrangement.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] The second attentive stage of the model incorporates cross-dimensional processing, and the actual identification of an object is done and information about the target object is put together.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] This theory has not always been what it is today; there have been disagreements and problems with its proposals that have allowed the theory to be amended and altered over time, and this criticism and revision has allowed it to become more accurate in its description of visual search.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] There have been disagreements over whether or not there is a clear distinction between feature detection and other searches that use a master map accounting for multiple dimensions in order to search for an object.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Some psychologists support the idea that feature integration is completely separate from this type of master map search, whereas many others have decided that feature integration incorporates this use of a master map in order to locate an object in multiple dimensions.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] The FIT also explains that there is a distinction between the brain's processes that are being used in a parallel versus a focal attention task.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Chan and Hayward have conducted multiple experiments supporting this idea by demonstrating the role of dimensions in visual search.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] While exploring whether or not focal attention can reduce the costs caused by dimension-switching in visual search, they explained that the results collected supported the mechanisms of the feature integration theory in comparison to other search-based approaches.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] They discovered that single dimensions allow for a much more efficient search regardless of the size of the area being searched, but once more dimensions are added it is much more difficult to efficiently search, and the bigger the area being searched the longer it takes for one to find the target.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] A second main function of preattentive processes is to direct focal attention to the most "promising" information in the visual field.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] There are two ways in which these processes can be used to direct attention: bottom-up activation (which is stimulus-driven) and top-down activation (which is user-driven).
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] In the guided search model by Jeremy Wolfe, information from top-down and bottom-up processing of the stimulus is used to create a ranking of items in order of their attentional priority.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] In a visual search, attention will be directed to the item with the highest priority.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] If that item is rejected, then attention will move on to the next item and the next, and so forth.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] The guided search theory follows that of parallel search processing.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] An activation map is a representation of visual space in which the level of activation at a location reflects the likelihood that the location contains a target.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] This likelihood is based on preattentive, featural information of the perceiver.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] According to the guided search model, the initial processing of basic features produces an activation map, with every item in the visual display having its own level of activation.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Attention is demanded based on peaks of activation in the activation map in a search for the target.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Visual search can proceed efficiently or inefficiently.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] During efficient search, performance is unaffected by the number of distractor items.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] The reaction time functions are flat, and the search is assumed to be a parallel search.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Thus, in the guided search model, a search is efficient if the target generates the highest, or one of the highest activation peaks.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] For example, suppose someone is searching for red, horizontal targets.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Feature processing would activate all red objects and all horizontal objects.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Attention is then directed to items depending on their level of activation, starting with those most activated.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] This explains why search times are longer when distractors share one or more features with the target stimuli.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] In contrast, during inefficient search, the reaction time to identify the target increases linearly with the number of distractor items present.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] According to the guided search model, this is because the peak generated by the target is not one of the highest.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] During visual search experiments the posterior parietal cortex has elicited much activation during functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) and electroencephalography (EEG) experiments for inefficient conjunction search, which has also been confirmed through lesion studies.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Patients with lesions to the posterior parietal cortex show low accuracy and very slow reaction times during a conjunction search task but have intact feature search remaining to the ipsilesional (the same side of the body as the lesion) side of space.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Ashbridge, Walsh, and Cowey in (1997) demonstrated that during the application of transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS) to the right parietal cortex, conjunction search was impaired by 100 milliseconds after stimulus onset.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] This was not found during feature search.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Nobre, Coull, Walsh and Frith (2003) identified using functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) that the intraparietal sulcus located in the superior parietal cortex was activated specifically to feature search and the binding of individual perceptual features as opposed to conjunction search.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Conversely, the authors further identify that for conjunction search, the superior parietal lobe and the right angular gyrus elicit bilaterally during fMRI experiments.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] In contrast, Leonards, Sunaert, Vam Hecke and Orban (2000) identified that significant activation is seen during fMRI experiments in the superior frontal sulcus primarily for conjunction search.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] This research hypothesises that activation in this region may in fact reflect working memory for holding and maintaining stimulus information in mind in order to identify the target.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Furthermore, significant frontal activation including the ventrolateral prefrontal cortex bilaterally and the right dorsolateral prefrontal cortex were seen during positron emission tomography for attentional spatial representations during visual search.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] The same regions associated with spatial attention in the parietal cortex coincide with the regions associated with feature search.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Furthermore, the frontal eye field (FEF) located bilaterally in the prefrontal cortex, plays a critical role in saccadic eye movements and the control of visual attention.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Moreover, research into monkeys and single cell recording found that the superior colliculus is involved in the selection of the target during visual search as well as the initiation of movements.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Conversely, it also suggested that activation in the superior colliculus results from disengaging attention, ensuring that the next stimulus can be internally represented.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] The ability to directly attend to a particular stimuli during visual search experiments has been linked to the pulvinar nucleus (located in the midbrain) while inhibiting attention to unattended stimuli.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Conversely, Bender and Butter (1987) found that during testing on monkeys, no involvement of the pulvinar nucleus was identified during visual search tasks.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] There is evidence for the V1 Saliency Hypothesis that the primary visual cortex (V1) creates a bottom-up saliency map to guide attention exogenously, and this V1 saliency map is read out by the superior colliculus which receives monosynaptic inputs from V1.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] There is a variety of speculation about the origin and evolution of visual search in humans.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] It has been shown that during visual exploration of complex natural scenes, both humans and nonhuman primates make highly stereotyped eye movements.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Furthermore, chimpanzees have demonstrated improved performance in visual searches for upright human or dog faces, suggesting that visual search (particularly where the target is a face) is not peculiar to humans and that it may be a primal trait.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Research has suggested that effective visual search may have developed as a necessary skill for survival, where being adept at detecting threats and identifying food was essential.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] The importance of evolutionarily relevant threat stimuli was demonstrated in a study by LoBue and DeLoache (2008) in which children (and adults) were able to detect snakes more rapidly than other targets amongst distractor stimuli.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] However, some researchers question whether evolutionarily relevant threat stimuli are detected automatically.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Over the past few decades there have been vast amounts of research into face recognition, specifying that faces endure specialized processing within a region called the fusiform face area (FFA) located in the mid fusiform gyrus in the temporal lobe.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Debates are ongoing whether both faces and objects are detected and processed in different systems and whether both have category specific regions for recognition and identification.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Much research to date focuses on the accuracy of the detection and the time taken to detect the face in a complex visual search array.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] When faces are displayed in isolation, upright faces are processed faster and more accurately than inverted faces, but this effect was observed in non-face objects as well.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] When faces are to be detected among inverted or jumbled faces, reaction times for intact and upright faces increase as the number of distractors within the array is increased.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Hence, it is argued that the 'pop out' theory defined in feature search is not applicable in the recognition of faces in such visual search paradigm.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Conversely, the opposite effect has been argued and within a natural environmental scene, the 'pop out' effect of the face is significantly shown.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] This could be due to evolutionary developments as the need to be able to identify faces that appear threatening to the individual or group is deemed critical in the survival of the fittest.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] More recently, it was found that faces can be efficiently detected in a visual search paradigm, if the distracters are non-face objects, however it is debated whether this apparent 'pop out' effect is driven by a high-level mechanism or by low-level confounding features.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Furthermore, patients with developmental prosopagnosia, who have impaired face identification, generally detect faces normally, suggesting that visual search for faces is facilitated by mechanisms other than the face-identification circuits of the fusiform face area.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Patients with forms of dementia can also have deficits in facial recognition and the ability to recognize human emotions in the face.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] In a meta-analysis of nineteen different studies comparing normal adults with dementia patients in their abilities to recognize facial emotions, the patients with frontotemporal dementia were seen to have a lower ability to recognize many different emotions.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] These patients were much less accurate than the control participants (and even in comparison with Alzheimer's patients) in recognizing negative emotions, but were not significantly impaired in recognizing happiness.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Anger and disgust in particular were the most difficult for the dementia patients to recognize.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Face recognition is a complex process that is affected by many factors, both environmental and individually internal.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Other aspects to be considered include race and culture and their effects on one's ability to recognize faces.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Some factors such as the cross-race effect can influence one's ability to recognize and remember faces.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Research indicates that performance in conjunctive visual search tasks significantly improves during childhood and declines in later life.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] More specifically, young adults have been shown to have faster reaction times on conjunctive visual search tasks than both children and older adults, but their reaction times were similar for feature visual search tasks.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] This suggests that there is something about the process of integrating visual features or serial searching that is difficult for children and older adults, but not for young adults.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Studies have suggested numerous mechanisms involved in this difficulty in children, including peripheral visual acuity, eye movement ability, ability of attentional focal movement, and the ability to divide visual attention among multiple objects.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Studies have suggested similar mechanisms in the difficulty for older adults, such as age related optical changes that influence peripheral acuity, the ability to move attention over the visual field, the ability to disengage attention, and the ability to ignore distractors.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] (2008) provides neurological evidence for the fact that older adults have slower reaction times during conjunctive searches compared to young adults.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Event-related potentials (ERPs) showed longer latencies and lower amplitudes in older subjects than young adults at the P3 component, which is related to activity of the parietal lobes.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] This suggests the involvement of the parietal lobe function with an age-related decline in the speed of visual search tasks.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Results also showed that older adults, when compared to young adults, had significantly less activity in the anterior cingulate cortex and many limbic and occipitotemporal regions that are involved in performing visual search tasks.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Research has found that people with Alzheimer's disease (AD) are significantly impaired overall in visual search tasks.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] People with AD manifest *enhanced* spatial cueing, but this benefit is only obtained for cues with high spatial precision.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Abnormal visual attention may underlie certain visuospatial difficulties in patients with (AD).
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] People with AD have hypometabolism and neuropathology in the parietal cortex, and given the role of parietal function for visual attention, patients with AD may have hemispatial neglect, which may result in difficulty with disengaging attention in visual search.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] (2000) investigated the ability of patients with AD to perform various types of visual search tasks.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Their results showed that search rates on "pop-out" tasks were similar for both AD and control groups, however, people with AD searched significantly slower compared to the control group on a conjunction task.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] One interpretation of these results is that the visual system of AD patients has a problem with feature binding, such that it is unable to communicate the different feature descriptions for the stimulus efficiently.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Binding of features is thought to be mediated by areas in the temporal and parietal cortex, and these areas are known to be affected by AD-related pathology.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Another possibility for the impairment of people with AD on conjunction searches is that there may be some damage to general attentional mechanisms in AD, and therefore any attention-related task will be affected, including visual search.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] (2000) detected a double dissociation with their experimental results on AD and visual search.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Earlier work was carried out on patients with Parkinson's disease (PD) concerning the impairment patients with PD have on visual search tasks.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] In those studies, evidence was found of impairment in PD patients on the "pop-out" task, but no evidence was found on the impairment of the conjunction task.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] As discussed, AD patients show the exact opposite of these results: normal performance was seen on the "pop-out" task, but impairment was found on the conjunction task.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] This double dissociation provides evidence that PD and AD affect the visual pathway in different ways, and that the pop-out task and the conjunction task are differentially processed within that pathway.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Studies have consistently shown that autistic individuals performed better and with lower reaction times in feature and conjunctive visual search tasks than matched controls without autism.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Several explanations for these observations have been suggested.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] One possibility is that people with autism have enhanced perceptual capacity.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] This means that autistic individuals are able to process larger amounts of perceptual information, allowing for superior parallel processing and hence faster target location.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Second, autistic individuals show superior performance in discrimination tasks between similar stimuli and therefore may have an enhanced ability to differentiate between items in the visual search display.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] A third suggestion is that autistic individuals may have stronger top-down target excitation processing and stronger distractor inhibition processing than controls.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] (2008) used an event-related functional magnetic resonance imaging design to study the neurofunctional correlates of visual search in autistic children and matched controls of typically developing children.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Autistic children showed superior search efficiency and increased neural activation patterns in the frontal, parietal, and occipital lobes when compared to the typically developing children.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Thus, autistic individuals' superior performance on visual search tasks may be due to enhanced discrimination of items on the display, which is associated with occipital activity, and increased top-down shifts of visual attention, which is associated with the frontal and parietal areas.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] In the past decade, there has been extensive research into how companies can maximise sales using psychological techniques derived from visual search to determine how products should be positioned on shelves.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Pieters and Warlop (1999) used eye tracking devices to assess saccades and fixations of consumers while they visually scanned/searched an array of products on a supermarket shelf.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Their research suggests that consumers specifically direct their attention to products with eye-catching properties such as shape, colour or brand name.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] This effect is due to a pressured visual search where eye movements accelerate and saccades minimise, thus resulting in the consumer's quickly choosing a product with a 'pop out' effect.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] This study suggests that efficient search is primarily used, concluding that consumers do not focus on items that share very similar features.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] The more distinct or maximally visually different a product is from surrounding products, the more likely the consumer is to notice it.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] Janiszewski (1998) discussed two types of consumer search.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] One search type is goal directed search taking place when somebody uses stored knowledge of the product in order to make a purchase choice.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] This occurs when the consumer has minimal previous knowledge about how to choose a product.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] It was found that for exploratory search, individuals would pay less attention to products that were placed in visually competitive areas such as the middle of the shelf at an optimal viewing height.
[src:gestalt-visualization/visual-search] This was primarily due to the competition in attention meaning that less information was maintained in visual working memory for these products.
